{
  "doc_id": "27448",
  "text": "Recently, two analyses [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ) of sequenced bacterial genomes have revealed the existence of more than 100 type VI secretion system (T6SS)-like loci, and these studies suggest that the FPIencoded secretion system is perhaps an outlier among the T6SSs. We previously identified the FPI-encoded proteins IglA, IglB, VgrG, PdpB (IcmF) and DotU as having deduced amino acid sequence similarity to T6SS components found in other bacteria [CITATION_3] , although these five proteins fall far short of comprising the core of at least 13 proteins thought to be part of a T6SS [CITATION_4] . Substantial evidence that the FPI encodes a secretion system comes from the finding that IglI and VgrG are secreted to the cytosol of macrophages [CITATION_5] . However, recent work has failed to confirm the FPI-dependent secretion of IglI (Bröms et al., 2011) , and no FPI-encoded secreted effector protein has been identified.",
